Sure, here's an example implementation of the Kalman sequence filter in GNU Octave:

```octave
function [x, P] = kalman_sequence_filter(y, A, B, C, Q, R)
    % y: measurement sequence
    % A: state transition matrix
    % B: control input matrix
    % C: measurement matrix
    % Q: process noise covariance matrix
    % R: measurement noise covariance matrix
    % x: filtered state sequence
    % P: filtered state covariance sequence

    % Initialize state and covariance sequences
    x = zeros(size(y, 1)), size(y, 2)));
    P = zeros(size(y, 1)), size(y, 2)));
    P(1, :, :) = eye(size(y, 2)));

    % Iterate over measurement sequence
    for k = 1:size(y, 1))
        % Predict state and covariance
        x_pred = A * x(k, :, :));
        P_pred = A * P(k, :, :)) * A' + Q;

        % Update state and covariance
        y_pred = C * x_pred;
        S = C * P_pred * C' + R;
        K = P_pred * C' / S;
        x(k+1, :, :) = x_pred + K * (y(k, :, :)) - y_pred);
        P(k+1, :, :)) = (eye(size(y, 2)))) - K * C) * P_pred;

    end

end
```

This implementation assumes that the measurement sequence `y` is a 2D array with dimensions `(num_measurements, num_states)`. The state transition matrix `A`, control input matrix `B`, measurement matrix `C`, process noise covariance matrix `Q`, and measurement noise covariance matrix `R` are all assumed to be 2D arrays with dimensions `(num_states, num_states)`, `(num_states, num_controls)`, `(num_measurements, num_states)`, `(num_states, num_states)`, and `(num_measurements, num_measurements)`, respectively.

The filtered state sequence `x` and filtered state covariance sequence `P` are both assumed to be 3D arrays with dimensions `(num_measurements+1, num_states, num_states)`, respectively.

