The issue you are facing is likely due to the fact that the UI is not being reloaded after a note is deleted. 

To resolve this issue, you can use the `load` function in Sveltekit to reload the UI after a note is deleted. 

Here's an example of how you can use the `load` function to reload the UI after a note is deleted:

```javascript
// In your page component
<script>
  import { onMount } from 'svelte';
  import { page } from '$app/stores';

  let notes = [];

  // Load notes from server
  async function loadNotes() {
    const response = await fetch('/api/notes');
    notes = await response.json();
  }

  // Delete a note
  async function deleteNote(noteId) {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/notes/${noteId}`), {
      method: 'DELETE'
    });
    if (response.ok) {
      await loadNotes();
    }
  }

  // Reload notes when the page is loaded
  onMount(async () => {
    await loadNotes();
  });

  // Reload notes when the page is reloaded
  $: async () => {
    await loadNotes();
  };

  // Delete a note when the form is submitted
  async function handleDeleteNote(event) {
    event.preventDefault();
    const noteId = event.target.elements.noteId.value;
    await deleteNote(noteId);
  }

  // Render the UI
  function renderNotes() {
    return notes.map(note => (
      <div class="note">
        <h2>{note.title}</h2>
        <p>{note.content}</p>
        <form on:submit|preventDefault={handleDeleteNote}>
          <input type="hidden" name="noteId" value={note.id} />
          <button type="submit">Delete</button>
        </form>
      </div>
    )));
  }
</script>

<!-- Render the UI -->
<div class="notes">
  {notes.length > 0 ? renderNotes() : <p>No notes found.</p>}
</div>
```

In this example, we have defined a `loadNotes` function that loads the notes from the server. We have also defined a `deleteNote` function that deletes a note from the server and reloads the notes from the server. 

We have also defined a `handleDeleteNote` function that is called when the form is submitted. This function calls the `deleteNote` function with the ID of the note that is being deleted. 

Finally, we have defined a `renderNotes` function that is called to render the list of notes. This function maps over the `notes` array and returns an array of `div` elements that represent each note. 

With this implementation, when a note is deleted using the form actions, the `deleteNote` function is called, which deletes the note from the server and reloads the notes from the server. The `loadNotes` function is called, which loads the notes from the server and updates the `notes` array. Finally, the `renderNotes` function is called, which maps over the `notes` array and returns an array of `div` elements that represent each note. The updated list of notes is then rendered in the UI.

Here's an example of how you can write a Laravel Middleware to block users whose IP is not in the array assigned inside the middleware.

1. Create a new Middleware using the following command:

```
php artisan make:middleware BlockNonAssignedIPs
```

2. Open the newly created Middleware file located at `app/Http/Middleware/BlockNonAssignedIPs.php`.

3. Inside the Middleware class, add the following code:

```php
namespace App\Http\Middleware;

use Closure;
use Illuminate\Support\Facades\Request;

class BlockNonAssignedIPs
{
    /**
     * Handle an incoming request.
     *
     * @param  \Illuminate\Http\Request  $request
     * @param  \Closure  $next
     * @return mixed
     */
    public function handle($request, Closure $next)
    {
        $allowedIPs = ['192.168.1.1', '10.0.0.1']; // Replace with your allowed IP addresses

        $clientIP = Request::ip();

        if (!in_array($clientIP, $allowedIPs))) {
            abort(403, 'Forbidden: Your IP address is not allowed to access this resource.');
        }

        return $next($request);
    }
}
```

4. Register the Middleware in the `app/Http/Kernel.php` file. Add the following line to the `$routeMiddleware` array:

```php
'block-non-assigned-ips' => \App\Http\Middleware\BlockNonAssignedIPs::class,
```

5. Now, you can use the Middleware in your routes by adding the following line to your route definition:

```php
Route::get('/my-resource', function () {
    return 'This is a protected resource.';
})->middleware('block-non-assigned-ips');
```

6. Save the changes and test the Middleware by accessing the protected resource from an IP address that is not in the allowed IP addresses array. You should see a 403 Forbidden error message.

