To manage the maximum number of running coroutines in PHP 8.2, you can use the `Swoole\Coroutine\Pool` class.

Here's an example of how to use the `Pool` class to limit the maximum number of running coroutines:

```php
use Swoole\Coroutine\Pool;

$pool = new Pool(5); // create a pool with a maximum of 5 coroutines

$pool->on('workerStart', function($worker) {
    // this function will be called when a new coroutine is created
});

$pool->on('workerError', function($worker, $exception) {
    // this function will be called when an error occurs in a coroutine
});

$pool->on('workerStop', function($worker) {
    // this function will be called when a coroutine is stopped
});

// add jobs to the pool
for ($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {
    $pool->submit(function($pool) use ($i) {
        // this function will be called when a new coroutine is created
        // you can add your job logic here
        echo "Job $i is running\n";
        sleep(1);
        echo "Job $i is finished\n";
    });
}

// wait for all coroutines to finish
$pool->wait();
```

In this example, we create a `Pool` object with a maximum of 5 coroutines. We then add 10 jobs to the pool using the `submit` method.

When a new coroutine is created, the `workerStart` event is triggered. When an error occurs in a coroutine, the `workerError` event is triggered. When a coroutine is stopped, the `workerStop` event is triggered.

Finally, we wait for all coroutines to finish using the `wait` method.

