Here's an example of how to use the strategy pattern in a banking app system:

```javascript
// Define the interface for the strategy
interface TransactionStrategy {
  executeTransaction(amount: number): void;
}

// Define the concrete strategies for different types of transactions
class DepositStrategy implements TransactionStrategy {
  executeTransaction(amount: number): void {
    console.log(`Depositing ${amount} into account`);
  }
}

class WithdrawalStrategy implements TransactionStrategy {
  executeTransaction(amount: number): void {
    console.log(`Withdrawing ${amount} from account`);
  }
}

class TransferStrategy implements TransactionStrategy {
  executeTransaction(amount: number): void {
    console.log(`Transferring ${amount} from account to another`);
  }
}

// Define the context class that uses the strategy pattern
class BankingApp {
  private transactionStrategy: TransactionStrategy;

  constructor(transactionStrategy: TransactionStrategy) {
    this.transactionStrategy = transactionStrategy;
  }

  public executeTransaction(amount: number): void {
    this.transactionStrategy.executeTransaction(amount);
  }
}

// Use the banking app with different transaction strategies
const depositStrategy = new DepositStrategy();
const withdrawalStrategy = new WithdrawalStrategy();
const transferStrategy = new TransferStrategy();

const bankingApp = new BankingApp(depositStrategy);
bankingApp.executeTransaction(100);

bankingApp.transactionStrategy = withdrawalStrategy;
bankingApp.executeTransaction(50);

bankingApp.transactionStrategy = transferStrategy;
bankingApp.executeTransaction(200);
```

In this example, we define an interface `TransactionStrategy` that defines the `executeTransaction` method that takes an `amount` parameter and returns `void`.

We then define three concrete strategies for different types of transactions: `DepositStrategy`, `WithdrawalStrategy`, and `TransferStrategy`. Each of these strategies implements the `TransactionStrategy` interface and provides its own implementation of the `executeTransaction` method.

We then define a context class `BankingApp` that uses the strategy pattern. This class has a private field `transactionStrategy` of type `TransactionStrategy`. The class has a constructor that takes a `transactionStrategy` parameter and sets the `transactionStrategy` field to this value.

The `BankingApp` class has a public method `executeTransaction` that takes an `amount` parameter and returns `void`. This method simply calls the `executeTransaction` method of the `transactionStrategy` field, passing in the `amount` parameter.

Finally, we use the `BankingApp` class with different transaction strategies. We create three instances of the concrete strategies: `depositStrategy`, `withdrawalStrategy`, and `transferStrategy`. We then create an instance of the `BankingApp` class, passing in the `depositStrategy` instance as the `transactionStrategy` parameter. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `bankingApp` instance, passing in the `100` value as the `amount` parameter. This should output the message "Depositing 100 into account".

We then change the `transactionStrategy` field of the `bankingApp` instance to the `withdrawalStrategy` instance. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `bankingApp` instance, passing in the `50` value as the `amount` parameter. This should output the message "Withdrawing 50 from account".

Finally, we change the `transactionStrategy` field of the `bankingApp` instance to the `transferStrategy` instance. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `bankingApp` instance, passing in the `200` value as the `amount` parameter. This should output the message "Transferring 200 from account to another".

