Here's an example C# program that sends a POST request with a client certificate attached:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net;
using System.Net.Security;
using System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        // Set up the client certificate
        X509Certificate2 clientCert = new X509Certificate2("path/to/client/cert.pfx", "password");

        // Set up the request
        HttpWebRequest request = (HttpWebRequest)WebRequest.Create("https://example.com/api/endpoint");
        request.Method = "POST";
        request.ContentType = "application/json";
        request.ClientCertificates.Add(clientCert);

        // Set up the SSL/TLS settings
        ServicePointManager.SecurityProtocol = SecurityProtocolType.Tls12;
        ServicePointManager.ServerCertificateValidationCallback = (sender, certificate, chain, sslPolicyErrors) => true;

        // Send the request and get the response
        HttpWebResponse response = (HttpWebResponse)request.GetResponse();
        using (Stream responseStream = response.GetResponseStream())
        {
            using (StreamReader reader = new StreamReader(responseStream)))
            {
                Console.WriteLine(reader.ReadToEnd());
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Note that you'll need to replace the path to the client certificate and the password with your own values.

To extract hashtags from text in C#, you can use regular expressions. Here's an example code:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Text.RegularExpressions;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string text = "This is a sample text with #hashtags and @mentions.";

        // Regular expression to match hashtags
        Regex regex = new Regex(@"#(\w+)");

        // Find all matches in the text
        MatchCollection matches = regex.Matches(text);

        // Print all hashtags found in the text
        Console.WriteLine("Hashtags found:");
        foreach (Match match in matches)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(match.Groups[1].Value);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, we use a regular expression to match hashtags in the text. The regular expression `#(\w+)` matches any text that starts with a `#` symbol followed by one or more word characters (letters, digits, and underscores). The parentheses around `\w+` capture the text that matches the regular expression, which in this case is the hashtag itself. We then use the `Regex.Matches` method to find all matches of the regular expression in the text. Finally, we print out all the hashtags found in the text using a `foreach` loop to iterate over the `MatchCollection` returned by `Regex.Matches`.

